I'd try to restructure it something more like this... set jumplabel=switcher if errorlevel 0 set jumplabel=errorhandler if errorlevel 1 set jumplabel=create_structure if errorlevel 2 set jumplabel=create_historical if errorlevel 3 set branch=stable if errorlevel 4 set branch=legacy if errorlevel 5 set branch=experimental if errorlevel 6 set branch=historical if errorlevel 7 set jumplabel=terminate if errorlevel 255 set jumplabel=errorhandler goto %jumplabel% :create_structure :: Double colons are treated as comments goto terminate :create_historical :: Placeholders for your code goto terminate :errorhandler echo An error has occurred. goto terminate :terminate pause exit /b I realize it's recommended to process errorlevel in reverse order, but note that I left the actual goto command after all the if statements, meaning it'll keep on changing the variables sequentially until it hits a condition that isn't met before it performs the actual goto jump. And yes, you can indeed jump to a set variable line.
